<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870730-0116 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:Incredible Truth</HL><DD> 07/30/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> MDESTDEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><TEXT>   No one was killed, thankfully, when the &quot;reflagged&quot; tanker Bridgeton hit a mine in the Persian Gulf. The episode may even have a beneficial fallout if it forces some of our allies to act like allies. Still, it's both clear and incredible that no one in the bloated Pentagon bureaucracy much pondered the possibility that the Iranians might use mines. As we wrote as the reflagging was debated, &quot;We sniff here the same kind of incoherence of purpose and mission that set the stage for the Marines' Lebanon debacle and the missile attack on the USS Stark.&quot; </TEXT></DOC>